                <h2>Michigan's Zero Tolerance Law: Critical Information for Underage GVSU Students</h2>
                <p>If you're a GVSU student under 21 years old, you need to understand Michigan's "Zero Tolerance" law. <strong>This law makes it illegal to drive with ANY detectable alcohol in your system - even amounts far below what would impair an adult driver.</strong></p>

                <h3>What is Michigan's Zero Tolerance Law?</h3>
                <p>Michigan's Zero Tolerance Law (MCL 257.625(6)) makes it illegal for anyone under 21 to operate a vehicle with a blood alcohol content (BAC) of <strong>0.02% or higher</strong>. To put this in perspective:</p>

                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Adult OWI threshold:</strong> 0.08% BAC (standard drunk driving)</li>
                    <li><strong>Zero Tolerance threshold (under 21):</strong> 0.02% BAC</li>
                    <li><strong>What 0.02% means:</strong> As little as ONE standard drink can put you over the limit</li>
                    <li><strong>Margin of error:</strong> Virtually zero - any alcohol consumption means you cannot legally drive</li>
                </ul>

                <p><strong>Important: The 0.02% threshold exists only to account for measurement error and substances like mouthwash or cough syrup.</strong> Michigan law effectively prohibits ANY alcohol consumption before driving if you're under 21.</p>

                <h3>How Little Alcohol Triggers Zero Tolerance Violations?</h3>
                <p>GVSU students are shocked to learn how little alcohol can result in a Zero Tolerance charge:</p>

                <ul>
                    <li><strong>One 12-ounce beer (5% ABV):</strong> Can produce 0.02-0.03% BAC in a 120-pound person</li>
                    <li><strong>One 5-ounce glass of wine:</strong> Can produce 0.02-0.04% BAC depending on body weight</li>
                    <li><strong>One standard mixed drink:</strong> Can easily exceed 0.02% BAC</li>
                    <li><strong>Tailgating or party before driving:</strong> Even hours later, you may still be over 0.02%</li>
                </ul>

                <p><strong>Common GVSU scenarios leading to Zero Tolerance arrests:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Having one drink at an off-campus party, then driving home hours later</li>
                    <li>Tailgating at GVSU football games, then driving</li>
                    <li>Drinking the night before, driving to morning classes with residual BAC</li>
                    <li>Being the "designated driver" but having "just one drink"</li>
                    <li>Traffic stop for minor violation (broken taillight, rolling stop) revealing any alcohol</li>
